11. Now run the application following the instructions from the initial setup.

You've now created an index page using React, Tailwind CSS, and components from Notus React. The page follows the features you described earlier, has RTL support for Arabic text, and is optimized for SEO.

You should customize the templates to match your desired design and replace the hard-coded content with dynamic content for logged-in users.

To create a `Root` component that includes all the previously created components, follow these steps.

1. In the `frontend/src/components` folder, create a new file called `Root.js`.

2. Populate `Root.js` with the following code:

```javascript
import React from 'react';
import Header from './Header';
import Sidebar from './Sidebar';
import HeroSection from './HeroSection';
import WhatWeDoSection from './WhatWeDoSection';
import Footer from './Footer';

const Root = () => {
  return (
    <>
      <Header />
      <Sidebar />
      <main>
        <HeroSection />
        <WhatWeDoSection />
      </main>
      <Footer />
    </>
  );
};

export default Root;
```

3. Now, go to your `frontend/src/App.js` file, and replace the individual component imports and usages with the `Root` component like this:

```javascript
import React from 'react';
import Root from './components/Root';

function App() {
  return (
    <div className="App">
      <Root />
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

By running the application now, you should see the same result as before, but with all the components organized into a single `Root` component, which makes the `App.js` cleaner and more manageable.

In MongoDB, data is stored in a flexible, JSON-like document format called BSON, which enables the storage of complex data types. The MongoDB terminology differs from traditional SQL databases: instead of tables, you have collections; instead of rows, you have documents; instead of columns, you have fields.

To create a MongoDB database and collections (analogous to SQL tables) with Node.js:

1. Set up a MongoDB Atlas cluster by following the steps described earlier. Obtain the connection string.

2. In your `backend` directory of the project, create a `.env` file if you haven't already, and add the MongoDB connection string:

```
ATLAS_URI=your_connection_string_here
```

3. Install `mongoose` in your backend. Mongoose is an Object Data Modeling (ODM) library, which helps manage relationships between data and provides schema validation.

```shell
npm install mongoose
```

4. In your `backend/server.js` file, import `mongoose` and update the file to establish a connection with your MongoDB Atlas cluster.

```javascript
const express = require("express");
const mongoose = require("mongoose"); // Import mongoose
const dotenv = require("dotenv");

dotenv.config();

const app = express();
const port = process.env.PORT || 5000;

app.use(express.json());

// Connect to MongoDB Atlas using the URI we defined in .env
mongoose.connect(
  process.env.ATLAS_URI,
  { useNewUrlParser: true, useUnifiedTopology: true, useCreateIndex: true, useFindAndModify: false }
);

const connection = mongoose.connection;
connection.once("open", () => {
  console.log("MongoDB database connection established successfully");
});

app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`Server is running on port: ${port}`);
});
```

5. Next, we will create Mongoose schemas, which define the structure of the documents in our collections. To do this, create a folder named `models` within your `backend` directory.

```shell
mkdir models
```

6. Now, create schema files for your data models. For instance, if you want to create a User and a Post model, you will create `User.js` and `Post.js` inside the `models` folder. Here's an example of how to define the schemas: 

```javascript
// models/User.js
const mongoose = require("mongoose");

const Schema = mongoose.Schema;

const userSchema = new Schema({
  name: { type: String, required: true },
  email: { type: String, required: true, unique: true },
  password: { type: String, required: true },
}, {
  timestamps: true,
});

const User = mongoose.model("User", userSchema);

module.exports = User;
```

```javascript
// models/Post.js
const mongoose = require("mongoose");

const Schema = mongoose.Schema;

const postSchema = new Schema({
  title: { type: String, required: true },
  content: { type: String, required: true },
  author: { type: Schema.Types.ObjectId, ref: 'User' },
}, {
  timestamps: true,
});

const Post = mongoose.model("Post", postSchema);

module.exports = Post;
```

7. With the schemas defined, you can now use them to add, read, update, and delete (CRUD operations) documents in your collections.

   Import your schemas in the `backend/server.js`, create routes, and perform CRUD operations. Here's an example using `User` and `Post` schemas:

```javascript
// ... import statements ...

const User = require('./models/User');
const Post = require('./models/Post');

// ... option configurations and app.listen() ...

app.get('/users', async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const users = await User.find();
    res.status(200).json(users);
  } catch (error) {
    res.status(500).json({ message: error.message });
  }
});
```

You can create more routes for handling other CRUD operations and use Mongoose to interact with the MongoDB collections and documents.

By following these steps, you can create a MongoDB database, define collections ("tables") with schemas, and perform CRUD operations using Node.js and Mongoose.
